1
00:01:29,668 --> 00:01:32,482
Hey, you! Switch the engine off!

2
00:01:33,124 --> 00:01:34,651
No, don't accelerate!

3
00:01:35,492 --> 00:01:36,801
Stop the engine!

4
00:03:18,147 --> 00:03:21,824
As a boy, I had a list of favorite jobs.

5
00:03:21,923 --> 00:03:23,865
My top 10.

6
00:03:24,324 --> 00:03:28,121
On top, it said in red letters, "Pilot."

7
00:03:31,971 --> 00:03:33,531
And in second position?

8
00:03:34,180 --> 00:03:36,089
Coffin-maker?

9
00:03:40,036 --> 00:03:41,246
I can't remember.

10
00:03:41,348 --> 00:03:43,901
The other nine were of no importance.

11
00:03:45,284 --> 00:03:46,232
Watch out!

12
00:03:48,259 --> 00:03:51,805
When it comes back, you have to duck!

13
00:03:52,227 --> 00:03:53,274
Okay.

14
00:03:57,795 --> 00:03:59,868
Beautiful flight.

15
00:04:06,820 --> 00:04:07,932
Wow, Grandpa!

16
00:04:08,036 --> 00:04:09,727
Straight into the kitchen window!

17
00:04:28,196 --> 00:04:30,170
<i>It's like a real piano!</i>

18
00:04:32,067 --> 00:04:33,660
<i>Did you say, "Thank you"?</i>

19
00:04:33,763 --> 00:04:34,711
<i>Thanks.</i>

20
00:04:43,044 --> 00:04:46,208
<i>The boy needs a real piano.</i>

21
00:04:46,307 --> 00:04:49,755
Mom, when do I get a real piano?

22
00:04:51,555 --> 00:04:55,003
Vitus, get dressed. We have to go.

23
00:04:56,675 --> 00:04:59,064
You'll have to ask your dad.

24
00:05:02,211 --> 00:05:03,159
Okay.

25
00:05:07,300 --> 00:05:10,234
Dad, when do I get a piano?

26
00:05:11,396 --> 00:05:13,305
You'll have to ask your godmother.

27
00:05:13,412 --> 00:05:15,321
Okay.

28
00:05:15,684 --> 00:05:18,334
Watch out! Don't touch anything.

29
00:05:18,755 --> 00:05:23,458
This thing can hear
five times better than a human ear.

30
00:05:24,259 --> 00:05:26,780
Bats can hear 10 times better.

31
00:05:26,883 --> 00:05:28,061
Yeah? Really?

32
00:05:28,547 --> 00:05:30,751
Put these on.

33
00:05:35,715 --> 00:05:37,308
I hear even less now.

34
00:05:37,764 --> 00:05:38,811
Wait a minute.

35
00:05:39,651 --> 00:05:41,560
You're right. There are no batteries.

36
00:05:41,923 --> 00:05:43,745
But when this thing is finished,

37
00:05:43,843 --> 00:05:46,745
everything will be put into a microchip,

38
00:05:46,851 --> 00:05:48,607
which will be built into this here.

39
00:05:48,707 --> 00:05:50,617
Then you'll hear as well as a cat.

40
00:05:51,139 --> 00:05:53,114
I'm going to call it Cat-Ear.

41
00:05:53,603 --> 00:05:55,937
Actually, Bat-Ear would be better.

42
00:05:56,772 --> 00:05:58,365
I would like that, too.

43
00:05:58,467 --> 00:06:01,784
Speaking of Bat-Ear,
I've got something for you.

44
00:06:02,724 --> 00:06:04,317
And in fact, it works.

45
00:06:04,900 --> 00:06:08,161
Press here, and it lights up.

46
00:06:08,579 --> 00:06:09,725
Look at the red light.

47
00:06:10,115 --> 00:06:14,043
There are two little microphones.

48
00:06:15,331 --> 00:06:19,193
<i>And then this.</i>

49
00:06:19,652 --> 00:06:22,335
<i>Now you can hear like a bat.</i>

50
00:06:23,171 --> 00:06:25,659
<i>Come to the window.</i>

51
00:06:37,284 --> 00:06:38,810
It's great, isn't it?

52
00:06:39,939 --> 00:06:41,532
<i>I wouldn't do that, Olga.</i>

53
00:06:41,636 --> 00:06:43,840
<i>Soon he'll be telling you what to do.</i>

54
00:06:44,131 --> 00:06:45,854
Vitus, hurry up and get dressed!

55
00:06:46,371 --> 00:06:47,898
Actually, I'll need that back.

56
00:06:52,196 --> 00:06:53,854
When's your appointment?

57
00:06:53,955 --> 00:06:55,516
Not till the afternoon.

58
00:06:56,771 --> 00:07:00,349
Damn, I can't find my transparencies.

59
00:07:00,643 --> 00:07:03,578
Does this have to happen now?
It's paradoxical!

60
00:07:03,683 --> 00:07:06,530
No, it's typical.

61
00:07:08,067 --> 00:07:10,139
Dad, what does "paradoxical" mean?

62
00:07:12,708 --> 00:07:15,074
- "Paradoxical" means...
- Leo.

63
00:07:15,619 --> 00:07:17,310
I'll tell you later.

64
00:07:17,412 --> 00:07:19,070
But I want to know it now.

65
00:07:19,491 --> 00:07:20,636
Two minutes.

66
00:07:21,315 --> 00:07:23,104
Okay, two minutes.

67
00:07:46,531 --> 00:07:47,775
Just a quick question.

68
00:07:48,643 --> 00:07:52,985
Could I work 70% instead of 30?

69
00:07:53,443 --> 00:07:57,087
Okay, but what about Vitus?

70
00:07:57,187 --> 00:07:59,489
We have a very expensive child.

71
00:07:59,587 --> 00:08:03,003
We have a babysitter now,
the daughter of our gem.

72
00:08:03,107 --> 00:08:04,089
Monti's daughter?

73
00:08:04,452 --> 00:08:05,400
Great.

74
00:08:10,275 --> 00:08:14,879
No wonder a lot of people
would rather do without a hearing aid

75
00:08:15,012 --> 00:08:17,761
and give up some quality of life

76
00:08:17,859 --> 00:08:20,095
than carry a snail shell behind their ears.

77
00:08:21,155 --> 00:08:23,937
You know that we generate 90%

78
00:08:24,035 --> 00:08:26,174
of our turnover with these snails.

79
00:08:26,276 --> 00:08:29,625
I know that, but if Phonaxis
wants to become a global player...

80
00:08:29,731 --> 00:08:33,506
Young people should wear
our hearing aids as fashion items, then?

81
00:08:33,604 --> 00:08:36,506
Maybe in fluorescent colors?

82
00:08:37,283 --> 00:08:39,585
Yes, that's exactly what I think.

83
00:08:39,972 --> 00:08:43,932
We have to beat the competition,
which isn't sleeping, either,

84
00:08:44,579 --> 00:08:50,394
with highly intelligent
and pretty hearing computers.

85
00:08:52,035 --> 00:08:54,556
That means, don't hide your hearing aid,

86
00:08:55,299 --> 00:08:59,554
but show it off and present it like jewelry.

87
00:09:01,283 --> 00:09:03,455
On the table, you can see my prototypes,

88
00:09:03,555 --> 00:09:05,792
the Cat-Ear and the Bat-Ear.

89
00:09:06,115 --> 00:09:09,148
The design might need a few changes,

90
00:09:09,251 --> 00:09:10,974
but this is all about the idea, isn't it?

91
00:09:11,075 --> 00:09:17,087
Sounds like you want to lead
the project yourself.

92
00:09:17,347 --> 00:09:19,900
That's exactly what I think.

93
00:09:20,419 --> 00:09:22,459
Why should I believe in you?

94
00:09:22,691 --> 00:09:24,862
You even dropped out of university!

95
00:09:27,075 --> 00:09:29,595
Because, otherwise,
I'll go to the competition.

96
00:09:32,835 --> 00:09:34,907
Thanks for the presentation.

97
00:09:36,547 --> 00:09:39,809
You'll be hearing from us.

98
00:09:42,627 --> 00:09:47,231
The other day, he read
about global warming to the children.

99
00:09:47,523 --> 00:09:49,084
He told them they would all have to die.

100
00:09:49,187 --> 00:09:51,195
The children started to cry.

101
00:09:51,299 --> 00:09:53,404
And then I get
the phone calls from the parents.

102
00:09:53,507 --> 00:09:56,638
Why don't you tell Vitus to read

103
00:09:57,475 --> 00:10:00,258
<i>The Wolf and the Seven Little Kids</i> to them.

104
00:10:00,355 --> 00:10:02,657
Actually, that's my job.

105
00:10:03,011 --> 00:10:07,135
Vitus should be at school, not kindergarten.

106
00:10:07,523 --> 00:10:10,207
And besides, he's very cheeky.

107
00:10:10,755 --> 00:10:14,017
Instead of calling me Mrs. Pfenninger.
He calls me Obelix.

108
00:10:15,299 --> 00:10:17,568
But that's a compliment.

109
00:10:17,667 --> 00:10:19,423
He loves Obelix.

110
00:10:32,003 --> 00:10:32,985
I'll take him with me.

111
00:10:33,091 --> 00:10:35,066
Come on, let's go.

112
00:10:36,035 --> 00:10:37,857
- Bye, Obelix.
- Bye.

113
00:10:38,051 --> 00:10:39,994
I've had enough.

114
00:10:41,091 --> 00:10:42,716
They're getting soggy.

115
00:10:54,115 --> 00:10:55,741
- I love you.
- I know.

116
00:10:55,843 --> 00:10:59,585
Don't wipe off the lipstick
so people can see that you're taken.

117
00:11:00,099 --> 00:11:02,554
- Bye, Vitus.
- Bye.

118
00:11:02,659 --> 00:11:04,547
See you in the foyer at 7:30.

119
00:11:08,611 --> 00:11:12,473
Listen, Vitus, you don't have
to go to kindergarten anymore.

120
00:11:13,219 --> 00:11:14,430
Cool.

121
00:11:14,659 --> 00:11:17,725
While I'm at work,
a babysitter will look after you.

122
00:11:18,243 --> 00:11:19,836
But I'm not a baby.

123
00:11:21,027 --> 00:11:24,027
Then just call her a girlfriend.
Isabel is coming tonight.

124
00:11:24,131 --> 00:11:26,368
We're going to a concert, okay?

125
00:11:26,755 --> 00:11:28,828
I'll have to practice tonight.

126
00:11:30,723 --> 00:11:32,828
You can practice all day.

127
00:11:34,115 --> 00:11:36,504
- Can I?
- Of course.

128
00:11:50,019 --> 00:11:52,921
Nobody's ever got to the top as fast as you.

129
00:12:05,059 --> 00:12:06,336
Ah, Isabel.

130
00:12:06,659 --> 00:12:07,772
Hello, Mrs. von Holzen.

131
00:12:07,907 --> 00:12:10,624
Call me Helen. Please come in.

132
00:12:13,763 --> 00:12:15,257
Okay.

133
00:12:17,955 --> 00:12:20,988
Vitus has a shower every evening.

134
00:12:21,123 --> 00:12:24,385
So now you know where to find everything.

135
00:12:24,515 --> 00:12:27,165
And, once again, never disturb Vitus

136
00:12:27,267 --> 00:12:29,274
- while he's practicing, okay?
- Okay.

137
00:12:29,571 --> 00:12:31,840
Take care. Bye, Vitus!

138
00:13:10,307 --> 00:13:11,255
Vitus?

139
00:13:11,363 --> 00:13:12,410
I'm reading.

140
00:13:16,419 --> 00:13:18,044
Can I come in?

141
00:13:18,147 --> 00:13:20,481
Be quiet. I want to read.

142
00:13:39,843 --> 00:13:43,072
Did you know
that it was me who made the bat?

143
00:13:43,619 --> 00:13:46,107
I gave it to you for your first birthday.

144
00:13:46,466 --> 00:13:48,092
It's called Abraham.

145
00:13:48,451 --> 00:13:50,491
- Abraham?
- Abraham.

146
00:13:50,883 --> 00:13:52,410
That's a beautiful name.

147
00:14:03,394 --> 00:14:05,249
Oh, my God, it's so big.

148
00:14:12,451 --> 00:14:15,101
Do you mind if we pick some flowers?

149
00:14:20,003 --> 00:14:23,167
It's all right, my little darling.

150
00:14:25,315 --> 00:14:27,617
I just need to pick some flowers.

151
00:14:33,187 --> 00:14:36,733
See? You just have to ask politely.

152
00:14:37,635 --> 00:14:40,002
Why are you picking flowers for my mother?

153
00:14:42,050 --> 00:14:44,506
Because she reminds me
of your grandmother.

154
00:14:45,634 --> 00:14:47,576
Can you show me a photo of her?

155
00:14:50,627 --> 00:14:54,304
She was too beautiful for a photo.

156
00:14:55,203 --> 00:14:57,756
Oh, no, we've just missed the train.

157
00:14:58,499 --> 00:15:00,768
We'll take the next one.

158
00:15:04,994 --> 00:15:07,962
The walls are freshly painted. New furniture.

159
00:15:08,611 --> 00:15:10,498
Have you suddenly become rich?

160
00:15:11,587 --> 00:15:13,343
What do you mean by rich?

161
00:15:14,147 --> 00:15:16,536
Would you like to wear one of my suits?

162
00:15:19,363 --> 00:15:23,007
If I'm not good enough
for your dinner party,

163
00:15:23,938 --> 00:15:25,978
feel free to cancel the invitation.

164
00:15:28,226 --> 00:15:30,844
You've brought some lovely flowers.

165
00:15:30,947 --> 00:15:33,794
Yes, they're from a very special shop.

166
00:15:34,946 --> 00:15:37,335
You're even more charming than your son.

167
00:15:37,443 --> 00:15:39,647
Well, that's not really hard.

168
00:15:40,835 --> 00:15:43,039
- Where's Vitus?
- In his room.

169
00:15:45,539 --> 00:15:47,361
Are you getting dressed up?

170
00:15:53,602 --> 00:15:56,319
I'm not into costume parties.

171
00:15:56,578 --> 00:15:58,553
Let's get away, Grandpa.

172
00:15:58,659 --> 00:16:02,587
That's impossible. You're the host.

173
00:16:03,459 --> 00:16:05,281
Have a pleasant evening.

174
00:16:29,507 --> 00:16:31,514
Cheers!

175
00:16:32,194 --> 00:16:33,983
You have a nice place here.

176
00:16:34,083 --> 00:16:35,424
A typical 1930s house.

177
00:16:35,523 --> 00:16:37,181
It's going to be pulled down soon.

178
00:16:37,283 --> 00:16:39,170
That's why the rent is low.

179
00:16:39,266 --> 00:16:44,831
To go public at the right moment
could be a stroke of genius.

180
00:16:44,930 --> 00:16:46,938
You want to go public with Phonaxis?

181
00:16:47,043 --> 00:16:48,603
I have a feeling

182
00:16:48,707 --> 00:16:53,279
that our Cat-Ear
will attract lots of speculators.

183
00:16:53,378 --> 00:16:57,241
It's either boom or bust.

184
00:16:57,635 --> 00:16:59,969
I do feel optimistic.

185
00:17:00,067 --> 00:17:02,816
But I'm still against going public.

186
00:17:03,715 --> 00:17:05,657
The stakes are too high.

187
00:17:05,763 --> 00:17:11,392
Mr. von Holzen,
you are our savior or our ruin.

188
00:17:11,491 --> 00:17:13,149
I hope I'm not either of them.

189
00:17:13,251 --> 00:17:15,706
Nick, take a look at that buffet!

190
00:17:15,810 --> 00:17:18,680
Yes, just help yourself.

191
00:17:18,946 --> 00:17:22,329
Thanks. We know how it works.

192
00:17:30,658 --> 00:17:32,185
Why does he hate me?

193
00:17:32,674 --> 00:17:35,424
Because your wife is more beautiful.

194
00:17:36,226 --> 00:17:37,175
True.

195
00:17:37,282 --> 00:17:38,657
You'll talk him round.

196
00:17:40,643 --> 00:17:43,545
I'm not musical at all.

197
00:17:44,098 --> 00:17:46,848
My godson, however,
is all the more musical.

198
00:17:47,330 --> 00:17:49,469
- Really?
- Yes, it's incredible.

199
00:17:49,987 --> 00:17:51,580
That's interesting.

200
00:17:51,938 --> 00:17:54,840
My husband wanted to become a pianist.

201
00:17:55,074 --> 00:17:56,057
Really?

202
00:17:57,507 --> 00:17:58,652
It was a long time ago.

203
00:18:04,674 --> 00:18:05,951
Oh, excuse me.

204
00:18:06,051 --> 00:18:07,327
Do you play the piano?

205
00:18:07,427 --> 00:18:09,314
No, our son does.

206
00:18:09,506 --> 00:18:12,059
Oh, a talented family.

207
00:18:12,419 --> 00:18:14,110
But surely not these difficult notes.

208
00:18:15,555 --> 00:18:18,337
Yes, he has a good teacher.

209
00:18:18,435 --> 00:18:20,923
He's been taking lessons for six months.

210
00:18:21,571 --> 00:18:22,683
For six months?

211
00:18:22,787 --> 00:18:24,412
You don't believe that yourself!

212
00:18:24,707 --> 00:18:26,846
He doesn't play like a maestro.

213
00:18:28,803 --> 00:18:29,751
Leo?

214
00:18:37,858 --> 00:18:40,858
Would you play something for us? No?

215
00:18:41,250 --> 00:18:43,039
Come on, only one piece.

216
00:18:43,395 --> 00:18:45,467
We'd all be delighted.

217
00:18:55,523 --> 00:18:56,984
What does he play?

218
00:18:57,826 --> 00:18:59,899
Robert Schumann's <i>Wild Rider.</i>

219
00:19:09,667 --> 00:19:10,844
Vitus.

220
00:19:10,946 --> 00:19:13,150
What a sweet little chap!

221
00:19:16,803 --> 00:19:19,552
You can sense that he's musical.

222
00:19:20,194 --> 00:19:21,176
Beautiful.

223
00:19:44,258 --> 00:19:45,851
Extraordinary.

224
00:19:46,882 --> 00:19:48,737
A real wunderkind.

225
00:19:49,762 --> 00:19:51,486
I've never seen anything like it.

226
00:20:07,842 --> 00:20:10,689
He's only six, but we do hope...

227
00:20:11,490 --> 00:20:13,279
Well, he didn't get it from me.

228
00:20:13,443 --> 00:20:16,705
They've told us that his IQ
is so high it's incalculable,

229
00:20:16,802 --> 00:20:19,039
but I don't know much about it.

230
00:20:19,139 --> 00:20:20,513
<i>I'm too stupid.</i>

231
00:20:20,611 --> 00:20:24,767
<i>I've been telling Leo</i>
<i>that we're raising a real talent here.</i>

232
00:20:25,571 --> 00:20:29,794
<i>Do you remember</i>
<i>the horoscope that I did for Vitus?</i>

233
00:20:33,539 --> 00:20:38,776
<i>You carry a huge responsibility,</i>

234
00:20:39,170 --> 00:20:41,025
<i>especially as his mother,</i>

235
00:20:41,923 --> 00:20:44,224
<i>- if you know what I mean.</i>
<i>- Yes.</i>

236
00:20:44,738 --> 00:20:48,862
<i>All of the world's great pianists</i>
<i>were so-called wunderkinds</i>

237
00:20:49,507 --> 00:20:51,295
<i>in their childhood.</i>

238
00:20:52,162 --> 00:20:54,017
<i>No exception.</i>

239
00:20:54,690 --> 00:20:56,992
<i>You really have to foster his talents.</i>

240
00:20:57,282 --> 00:20:58,526
<i>The earlier, the better.</i>

241
00:20:58,626 --> 00:21:01,048
<i>He should go straight to the conservatory.</i>

242
00:21:01,154 --> 00:21:06,140
<i>You don't just owe this to your son</i>
<i>but also to music.</i>

243
00:21:08,099 --> 00:21:13,598
Now the world knows
we have a real wunderkind

244
00:21:16,899 --> 00:21:19,616
<i>and a cheeky little monkey.</i>

245
00:21:21,859 --> 00:21:23,484
<i>Maybe Knaak was right.</i>

246
00:21:23,842 --> 00:21:25,664
<i>We have to foster his talents.</i>

247
00:21:26,339 --> 00:21:28,924
<i>What he doesn't learn now, he'll never learn.</i>

248
00:21:29,090 --> 00:21:32,832
We shouldn't put pressure on him.

249
00:21:32,930 --> 00:21:34,839
Otherwise, he might do the opposite.

250
00:21:35,235 --> 00:21:38,682
It won't work without a little pressure.

251
00:21:38,786 --> 00:21:40,695
Vitus needs that.

252
00:21:40,803 --> 00:21:41,817
Same as you.

253
00:21:45,762 --> 00:21:48,096
You're right in principle,

254
00:21:48,323 --> 00:21:52,032
but an academy is for adults.

255
00:21:52,675 --> 00:21:55,260
The boy doesn't even go to school yet.

256
00:21:55,362 --> 00:21:56,572
But didn't you...

257
00:21:56,674 --> 00:22:00,187
However, I have recognized his talent.

258
00:22:02,242 --> 00:22:04,762
We will accept him.

259
00:22:05,347 --> 00:22:06,939
Did you hear that, Vitus?

260
00:22:07,042 --> 00:22:09,595
I'll teach you myself.

261
00:22:10,018 --> 00:22:12,571
That's unbelievable!

262
00:22:13,891 --> 00:22:15,778
Thank you very much.

263
00:22:19,043 --> 00:22:22,785
Are you a concert pianist yourself?

264
